  "prompt": "What is the meaning of Urdu compound word \u201cghairat-e-ashiq\u201d?",
  "response": "The Urdu compound word \"ghairat-e-ashiq\" can be broken down into two parts: \"ghairat\" and \"ashiq.\"\n\n- \"Ghairat\" (\u063a\u06cc\u0631\u062a) in Urdu typically translates to \"honor,\" \"self-respect,\" or \"jealousy\" in English. It often refers to a sense of dignity or pride, particularly in the context of personal or familial honor.\n- \"Ashiq\" (\u0639\u0627\u0634\u0642) means \"lover\" in Urdu.\n\nWhen combined, \"ghairat-e-ashiq\" (\u063a\u06cc\u0631\u062a\u0650 \u0639\u0627\u0634\u0642) can be translated as \"the honor of a lover\" or \"the jealousy of a lover.\" This compound word encapsulates the intense feelings of pride, dignity, or possessiveness that a lover might feel in a romantic context. It suggests a deep emotional connection where the lover's honor or self-respect is tied to their relationship.",
